## Abstract

We propose **Gravitational Structural Collapse (GSC)** as a renormalized, scale-covariant framework in which the standard interpretation of cosmological redshift as *metric expansion* is replaced by a physically equivalent description: a **freeze-frame (conformally static) background spacetime** with a **time-evolving matter scale**. In this formulation, the observed growth of cosmological distances in atomic units is attributed to the **continuous shrinkage of bound matter** (equivalently, the growth of particle masses in a freeze-frame description), while **dimensionless local physics remains invariant**.

The core dynamical hypothesis of v10 is that the collapse of the characteristic matter scale is driven by **renormalization-group (RG) running of gravity**: the effective Newton coupling becomes strongly enhanced as the system approaches a critical ultraviolet scale. We replace all prior large-extra-dimension (ADD/LED) toy enhancements with a single RG-flow mechanism featuring a **sharp, pole-like crossover (Padé-type) enhancement** in the coupling. This provides a natural route to an effective phantom equation of state ($w_{\rm eff} < -1$) without introducing ad hoc fluid components.

A key conceptual addition is **energy bookkeeping**. In standard FLRW cosmology, global energy is not generally a Noether charge because a time-dependent background lacks a global timelike Killing symmetry. In the GSC freeze frame, a global time-translation symmetry is restored and total energy can be defined as a conserved Noether quantity, while the apparent “photon energy loss” of redshift is reinterpreted as the evolution of the detector scale.

GSC v10 is deliberately minimal: it highlights one **historical supporting diagnostic** beyond the LambdaCDM concordance model, namely the **sign of the redshift drift** ($dz/dt_0$) at high redshift. For the toy late-time histories considered here (monotonic accelerated collapse satisfying $H(z)<H_0(1+z)$ in the quasar range), these histories imply $\dot z>0$ at $z\sim 2$–5, in contrast with the standard expectation $\dot z<0$ in that range. This diagnostic remains testable with upcoming ultra-stable high-resolution spectroscopy (ELT/ANDES; precursor programs with VLT/ESPRESSO).
Because Sandage-Loeb is a kinematic relation, this is explicitly a **history-vs-history** test (`H(z)_GSC` versus `H(z)_\Lambda\mathrm{CDM}`), not a frame-label test.

